## Key Architectural Patterns

### 1. Clean Architecture
- **Domain Layer**: Business entities, value objects, and domain logic
- **Application Layer**: Use cases, DTOs, and application services
- **Infrastructure Layer**: Controllers, repositories, and external integrations

### 2. Domain-Driven Design (DDD)
- Rich domain models with business logic
- Repository pattern for data access
- Domain events for cross-module communication
- Value objects and entities

### 3. Command Query Separation (CQS)
- Commands: Modify state, return void or entity
- Queries: Read data, return data without side effects
- Automatic transaction management for commands

### 4. Event-Driven Architecture
- Domain events for loose coupling
- Event handlers for cross-module communication
- Automatic event dispatching after successful commands

## Module Architecture

Each module follows a consistent structure:

```
{module-name}/
├── {module-name}.module.ts    # Module configuration
├── constants.ts               # DI tokens
├── domain/                   # Business logic
│   ├── entities/            # Domain entities
│   ├── repositories/        # Repository interfaces
│   ├── mappers/             # Data transformation
│   ├── events/              # Domain events
│   └── enums/               # Domain enums
├── application/              # Application services
│   ├── use-cases/           # Business operations
│   ├── services/            # Application services
│   ├── dto/                 # Data transfer objects
│   └── exceptions/          # Domain exceptions
└── infrastructure/           # External concerns
    ├── controllers/         # HTTP endpoints
    ├── persistence/         # Database implementations
    ├── services/            # Infrastructure services
    └── event-handlers/      # Event processing
```

## Development Guidelines

### 1. Code Organization
- Follow the established module structure
- Use consistent naming conventions
- Implement proper separation of concerns

### 2. Dependency Injection
- Use DI tokens from constants.ts
- Avoid circular dependencies
- Export only necessary services

### 3. Error Handling
- Use domain-specific exceptions
- Implement proper validation
- Handle errors at appropriate layers

### 4. Testing
- Maintain high test coverage
- Test business logic independently
- Use proper mocking strategies

### 5. Documentation
- Document API endpoints with Swagger
- Use clear and descriptive names
- Maintain up-to-date documentation

## Common Patterns

### 1. Entity Creation
```typescript
// Use builder pattern for entities
const company = Company.builder('Company Name')
  .description('Description')
  .website('https://example.com')
  .build();
```

### 2. Use Case Implementation
```typescript
// Extend Command or Query base classes
export class CreateEntityUseCase extends Command<CreateEntityDto, Entity> implmenets ICreateEntityUseCase {
  protected async implementation(): Promise<Entity> {
    // Business logic here
  }
}
```

### 3. Repository Pattern
```typescript
// Define interface in domain, implement in infrastructure
export interface IEntityRepository {
  create(entity: Entity): Promise<Entity>;
  findById(id: string): Promise<Entity | null>;
}
```

### 4. Event Handling
```typescript
// Use domain events for cross-module communication
@EventsHandler(EntityCreatedEvent)
export class EntityCreatedEventHandler implements IEventHandler<EntityCreatedEvent> {
  async handle(event: EntityCreatedEvent): Promise<void> {
    // Handle event
  }
}
```

## Contributing

